					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the first quarter of 14th century. </p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent>360 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>230</height>
										<width>160</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>145</height>
										<width>100</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>360 (+ 1 unfoliated paper flyleaf at the beginning and at the end, 1 unfoliated parchment leaf at the beginning [folio 1a]).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>32 quires: i13+1, ii12, iii12, iv8, v8, vi8, vii8, viii8, ix8, x8, xi8, xii8, xiii12, xiv16, xv12, xvi16, xvii16, xviii12, xix12, xx16, xxi10, xxii16, xxiii14, xxiv8, xxv12, xxvi8, xxvii16, xxviii8, xxix12, xxx12, xxxi12, xxxii9+2. </p>
									<p>Quires marked by catchwords at the end. </p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>The margins have been cropped.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="3" ruledLines="31" writtenLines="30">
									<p>Ruling and pricking are sometimes visible. </p>
									<p>Smaller sections of Hafṭarot are marked at the beginning of each pericope with red Hebrew letters (א at the end of the first portion, ב at the beginning of the second, the end of the third portion is indicated by black א marking the end of the first Sabbath lection).</p>
									<p>The beginning of each of the five books of the Torah is distinguished by a whole page illumination in gold and colours, with the first word of the respective book in the middle. At the beginning of each of the Five Scrolls and Hafṭarot there is a similar ornament, but smaller.</p>
									<p>Masorah in micrographic design in numerous folios, often shaped to illustate the biblical text. </p>
									<p>Gilt edges.</p>
									<p>Small pen decorations on several folios.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="2">
							<summary>Main text in Ashkenazi square and semi-cursive script, punctuated; masoretic notes in Ashkenazi semi-cursive, not punctuated, of the 14th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">Ḥayim</name>, inscribed with his name (folios 313v, 358r); the word חיים is marked on folio 244v).</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Ya῾aḳov ben Mordekhai</name>: sold to <name type="person" role="owner">Yeḥiel ben Uri</name> on 28 of the month Iyyar 229 Hebrew[1469Gregorian]: inscribed in a purchase note (folio 358v). </p>
							<p>Italian and French translation of the same purchase note on a paper leaf foliated and presently part of quire xxii (dated 1824) (folio 359v). </p>
							<p>Italian insrciption: &apos;Questo libro .. venduto nel 28 Ijar 5229&apos; (18th-19th century) (folio 360r). </p>
							<p>English description of the manuscript, in pencil, partially illegible (19th century?) (folio 1r). </p>
						</additions>
